title: Regulatory Rules and Notices
body:
November 20, 2014

Visit the Bank's website for a listing of selected rules and regulations.
Regulatory Rules and Notices

The following proposed rule and final rule are reported in the Federal Register:

Federal Home Loan Bank Capital Stock and Capital Plans
Proposed rule
Federal Register: October 8, 2014
Agencies: Federal Housing Finance Agency (FHFA), Federal Housing Finance Board (FHFB)
Comments due: December 8, 2014

Summary: The proposed rule would transfer existing parts 931 and 933 of the FHFB regulations, which address requirements for Federal Home Loan Bank (FHLBank) capital stock and capital plans, to new Part 1277 of the FHFA regulations. The proposed rule would not make any substantive changes to these requirements, but would delete certain provisions that applied only to the one-time conversion of Bank stock to the new capital structure required by the Gramm-Leach- Bliley Act. It would also make certain clarifying changes so that the rules would more precisely reflect long-standing practices and requirements with regard to transactions in Bank stock. Most significantly, the proposed rule would add appropriate references to ‘‘former members’’ to clarify when former Bank members can be required to maintain investment in Bank capital stock after withdrawal from the Bank.

Procedures and General Definitions
Final rule
Federal Register: October 31, 2014
Agencies: FHFA, FHFB
Effective date: December 1, 2015

Summary: The FHFA is amending its regulations by relocating to the FHFA chapter of the Code of Federal Regulations an FHFB regulation relating to procedures under which the FHLBanks and the Office of Finance may request waivers, approvals, no action letters, and regulatory interpretations. The final rule modifies these regulations to make them also applicable to the Federal National Mortgage Association and the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation (collectively, Enterprises) and repeals provisions relating to the procedures for requesting case-by-case determinations. The final rule also relocates a definition to the general definitions section of the FHFA regulations.

title: Quarterly Dividend: 3.38%
body:
May 10, 2013
Bulletin No. 1429
Quarterly Dividend: 3.38%

Dear Chief Executive Officer:

On April 29, 2013, the Bank’s Board of Directors declared a cash dividend on the capital stock outstanding during the first quarter of 2013 at an annualized dividend rate of 3.38%, or $0.83342466 per share.

The quarterly dividend will be paid in cash on the capital stock outstanding to each shareholder during the quarter ended March 31, 2013, with the amount prorated for the period of time during the first quarter that the shareholder’s stock was outstanding.

The dividend will be credited to shareholders’ Settlement/Transaction Accounts with the Bank on Thursday, May 16, 2013, and the funds will become available for withdrawal on the following business day. The dividend payment will appear on the STA Statement, the Dividend Transaction Statement, and the Capital Stock Dividend Statement for your institution on the member website.

The Bank filed its first quarter 2013 financial report on Form 10-Q with the Securities and Exchange Commission today.

Sincerely,

Dean Schultz
President and Chief Executive Officer

title: Register today for our members-only webinar!
body:
February 19, 2013

2013 Economic and Fixed Income Outlook
Featuring Deutsche Bank’s Chief U.S. Economist and Other Experts

Join us on Wednesday, February 27, to learn more about the outlook for the U.S. economy and for fixed income investments. This interactive members-only webinar will feature Deutsche Bank’s chief U.S. economist, Joe LaVorgna, and a panel of Deutsche Bank’s fixed income strategists.

The webinar is free of charge, but you must register in advance. Once your webinar registration is complete, you will receive instructions from gotomeeting.com on how to dial in from your desk and participate in the live webinar online.

The webinar will begin at 11:00 a.m. PST. You are welcome to participate in the full two hours or join only for specific sessions. Each session will include time for questions and answers.

Agenda

11:00 a.m. to 11:30 p.m.

 

Economic Outlook

11:30 a.m. to 11:45 p.m.

 

Rates

11:45 a.m. to 12:15 p.m.

 

Agency MBS

12:15 p.m. to 12:30 p.m.

 

Agency Debt (Callables)

12:30 p.m. to 12:45 p.m.

 

Commercial Real Estate and Commercial MBS

12:45 p.m. to 1:00 p.m.

 

Asset-Backed Securities


Please forward this invitation to colleagues who may be interested in attending any of the sessions.

Register today!

Questions? Contact us at mkt_webinar@fhlbsf.com.

Moderator: Steve Cibull
Vice President and Managing Director, Federal Home Loan Bank of San Francisco

Deutsche Bank Speakers:

Economic Outlook:  Joseph A. LaVorgna
Joe is a Managing Director and serves as Chief U.S. Economist in charge of U.S. macroeconomic research for Global Markets. He joined Deutsche Bank in 1997 from Lehman Brothers, where he was a Vice President in the Fixed Income Division. Prior to joining Lehman, Joe was an economist at UBS Securities. He started his professional career at the Federal Reserve Bank of New York in 1992, where he was an economist on the Monetary Analysis and Projections Staff. Joe is a graduate of Vassar College and is a frequent commentator for CNBC and other media outlets. Joe and his colleagues were ranked #1 in Economics in the 2010 and 2011 Institutional Investors’ All-Star Fixed Income Poll.

Rates:  Stuart Sparks
Stuart joined Deutsche Bank in July 2011 as U.S. Interest Rate Strategist. He covers the macro outlook for the U.S. interest rates markets and creates derivatives trading strategies based on the firm’s macro views. Prior to joining Deutsche Bank, he was the Head of European Interest Rate Strategies at Credit Suisse in London, where his group covered government debt, interest rate derivatives, covered bonds, and inflation in the euro zone, UK, Switzerland, and Nordic regions. Stuart began his career at Lehman Brothers in New York in 1995, where at various times he covered U.S. Treasuries, GSE debt, and interest rate derivatives. He later served as North American Head of Derivatives Strategy at JPMorgan Chase. He has a B.A. in Economics and an M.B.A. in Finance from Vanderbilt University, and studied at Universitaet Fredericiana Karlsruhe (TH) in Germany.

Agency MBS:  Steven Abrahams
Steve is a Managing Director and Head of MBS and Securitization Research at Deutsche Bank. His team provides market analysis and investment advice in residential, commercial, and consumer securitized products. Steve joined Deutsche Bank in March 2010 from Citadel Investment Group. He previously was a Senior Managing Director at Bear Stearns, where his agency MBS and global rates research team was regularly ranked by Institutional Investor. In nearly 20 years on Wall Street, he has also held senior positions at Freddie Mac and Morgan Stanley. Steve currently teaches as an adjunct professor of finance and economics at Columbia Business School. He holds a Ph. D. from Columbia University and a B.S. from Northwestern University.

Agency Debt:  Daniel Sorid
Daniel joined Deutsche Bank in July 2010 as a U.S. Interest Rate Strategist. He covers the U.S. agency market, including U.S. GSE debentures and dollar-denominated debt issued by sovereigns, supranationals and foreign agencies. He received a B.A., M.B.A., and an M.S. in Journalism from Columbia University, where he was a Knight-Bagehot Fellow in Economics and Business Journalism.

Commercial Real Estate and Commercial MBS:  Harris Trifon
Harris joined Deutsche Bank in 2009 and is currently Global Head of the CRE debt research team. He joined the firm from Standard & Poor’s, where he spent the previous four years as head of the fixed-rate CMBS surveillance team and led the internal and external research efforts. Prior to joining S&P, Harris worked in the interest-rate derivative trading groups at the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi and BNP Paribas. Harris graduated with a B.A. from the University of Florida and an M.S. from New York University.

Asset-Backed Securities:  Elen Callahan
Elen is a Director in Deutsche Bank’s Securitization Research group, specializing in non-mortgage ABS research and strategy. Elen joined Deutsche Bank in 2003 from the ABS research group of Credit Suisse First Boston (CSFB), where she covered credit cards, autos, and student loans. Prior to joining CSFB, she was a buy-side ABS analyst active in the credit card, auto, and home equity markets. Elen is a graduate of New York University.

Fall 2015

Delivering Life-Changing Results

Sponsors for Educational Opportunity (SEO) Scholars is a free, eight-year academic program that gets low-income public high school students to, and through, college. After decades of success in New York City, including a 95% graduation rate, the program came to San Francisco in 2011 and graduated its first class of scholars in 2015, with help from an AHEAD grant sponsored by member Wells Fargo Financial National Bank.

NEWS


UPCOMING EVENTS

2015 AHEAD Awards

The Bank awarded $1 million in grants to innovative projects and programs that foster economic development and promote community stability and self-sufficiency in Arizona, California, and Nevada.


Community Support Review

A list of Bank members currently selected for Community Support Review by the Federal Housing Finance Agency is available on the Banks website. The FHFA encourages community groups and other interested parties to submit public comments on the community support activities of the institutions under review in this cycle. Comments are due by December 31, 2015.


AHP Recipient is Reader's Choice Winner

Mercy Housings Vera Haile Senior Community, which received a $900,000 AHP grant through member Silicon Valley Bank, was named 2015s best affordable housing development for seniors by readers of Affordable Housing Finance Magazine.

Grand Opening of 1585 Studios

October 29, 2015

First Community Housing will celebrate the grand opening of 1585 Studios, an affordable rental project that will provide 27 studio units to low-income developmentally disabled adults in Santa Clara County. Housing Choices Coalition, a nonprofit organization that works with developmentally disabled populations, will provide supportive services on-site. The project received a $260,000 AHP grant through member Silicon Valley Bank.
Learn More


LTSC 35th Anniversary Celebration

November 4, 2015

The Bank is a sponsor of Little Tokyo Service Centers 35th Anniversary Celebration, which will celebrate the organizations past accomplishments and introduce new initiatives. LTSC Executive Director Dean Matsubayashi currently serves as vice chair of the Bank's Affordable Housing Advisory Council.
Learn More


CAL-ALHFA Annual Meeting

November 12, 2015

The Bank is a sponsor of the California Association of Local Housing Finance Agencies annual meeting in Sacramento. This years theme is A Re-Examination of Critical Affordable Housing Policies. Anita Adams,VP, Directorof Affordable Housing at the Bank, will moderate a panel discussion on rent control at the event.

title: Community Works - Fall 2015

body:
November 13, 2015
Bulletin No. 1490
Community Support Programs:
Tools and Resources for Housing and Economic Development

To: All Members and Interested Community Groups

The Bank offers a number of valuable tools and resources designed to help our members and their community partners build strong and vibrant communities. We invite you to learn more about the support we provide for targeted community lending and affordable housing and economic development in Arizona, California, Nevada, and other regions our members serve.

Affordable Housing Program (AHP): Competitive AHP and AHP Set-Aside Programs

Each year, we contribute 10% of our net income from the preceding year to the AHP for projects and programs that create affordable housing opportunities for families and individuals earning up to 80% of the area median income. The majority of the funds are awarded through a competitive application process and used by members to help finance the development, acquisition, or rehabilitation of rental and owner-occupied multifamily and single-family housing. A portion of the funds is set aside for our first-time homebuyer programs, IDEA and WISH. In 2015, we awarded $45 million in grants in the annual AHP funding competition and allocated $9 million for the IDEA and WISH programs.

Competitive AHP
AHP grants are awarded through a competitive application process and support a wide range of rental and owner-occupied projects, from historic preservation and adaptive reuse to new construction and rehabilitation of rental or owner-occupied housing. Bank members submit applications for these grants in partnership with community-based affordable housing project sponsors. The next application cycle will begin in the first quarter of 2016.

Individual Development and Empowerment Account (IDEA) Program
The IDEA Program provides matching grants through Bank members to first-time homebuyers saving to buy a home through an Individual Development Account or by participating in a Family Self-Sufficiency or lease-to-own program. Eligible low- and moderate-income households can receive 3-to-1 matching grants of up to $15,000 for the purchase of a home, which can be applied to the downpayment or closing costs. The Bank allocates IDEA funds once a year to members based on program eligibility. The next application cycle will take place during the first quarter of 2016.

Workforce Initiative Subsidy for Homeownership (WISH) Program
The WISH Program provides matching grants through Bank members to working families and individuals who are ready to make the transition from renting to owning. Eligible low- and moderate-income households can receive 3-to-1 matching grants of up to $15,000 for the purchase of a home, which can be applied to the downpayment or closing costs. The Bank allocates WISH funds once a year to members based on program eligibility. The next application cycle will take place during the first quarter of 2016.

Access to Housing and Economic Assistance for Development (AHEAD) Program
AHEAD grants support the efforts of members, working with local community organizations, to give a critical, early-stage boost to targeted economic development projects that create or preserve jobs, facilitate improvements to public or private infrastructure, or deliver social services, training and education programs, and other services and programs that benefit lower-income neighborhoods. The Bank allocates AHEAD funds annually, and individual grants are awarded to members based on project eligibility and evaluation of the application. The Bank awarded $1 million in AHEAD grants in 2015. The next application cycle will take place during the second quarter of 2016.

Community Investment Cash Advance (CICA) Credit Programs

Advances for Community Enterprise (ACE)
Members may use ACE credit to provide funds for projects and activities that result in the creation or retention of jobs or provide services or other benefits for low- and moderate-income people and communities. Funds may be used to support community lending and economic development, including small business, commercial and industrial activities, community facilities, and public works. ACE advances are priced lower than regular Bank advances and are available throughout the year for a variety of credit products in a wide range of maturities.

Community Investment Program (CIP)
Members may use CIP credit for a variety of targeted financing activities, such as funding mortgages, financing first-time homebuyer programs, and creating and maintaining affordable housing for households with incomes at or below 115% of the area median income. CIP advances are priced lower than regular Bank advances and are available throughout the year for a variety of credit products in a wide range of maturities.

Community Investment Letters of Credit
The Bank's standby letters of credit are available to members throughout the year at favorable rates to provide credit enhancement and support for the financing of housing and economic development projects that otherwise meet ACE and CIP eligibility requirements. Because the Bank is rated Aaa by Moody's and AA+ by Standard & Poor's, Bank letters of credit may enablemembers to obtain a Aaa or AA+ rating on tax-exempt bond and note transactions that their institutions support.

Borrowing Capacity for Community Financial Institution (CFI) Members

To promote economic development lending by our CFI members, the Bank provides borrowing capacity to CFI members on small business, small agribusiness, and small farm loans when they are pledged under a blanket lien. A CFI is an FDIC-insured depository with average total assets of less than $1.123 billion (to be adjusted each year by the annual percentage increase in the Consumer Price Index).

Community Lending Plan Initiatives

As part of the Banks annual Community Lending Plan, we:

  • offer application and compliance training and technical assistance for the Bank's programs and products;
  • develop and maintain relationships with community and economic development organizations;
  • link community-based organizations to sources of technical assistance, experienced partners in community development, and advocacy groups;
  • support the efforts of members to address the needs of veterans and at-risk youth; and
  • support the efforts of members and their community partners to promote healthy neighborhoods.

We encourage you to visit fhlbsf.com for more information on the community programs described in this notice. Program application information, news about trainings and other events, and stories of how members have successfully used our programs are also available online.
